            <h3>Input</h3>
            <p>In Java, you can take input from the user or from other sources (such as files) using various methods and classes. The most common way to take input from the user is through the console using the Scanner class, but you can also use other input sources like command-line arguments or reading from files.</p>
            <h4>Using Scanner object</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>Import the Scanner class from the Java.util package.</li>
                <li>Create a Scanner object to read input from the keyboard.</li>
                <li>Use Scanner methods (next(), nextInt(), nextDouble(), nextLine(), etc.) to read user input.</li>
                <li>Close the Scanner when finished to release resources.</li>
            </ol>
            <div class="code_container">
                <div class="code_wrapper">
                    <pre>
                        <code id="code" class="language-Java">
                            import Java.util.Scanner;
public class MyClass {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        //Code for identifiers
         // Create a Scanner object to read from the console
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        // Prompt the user for input
        System.out.print("Enter your name: ");
        // Read a line of text from the console
        String name = scanner.nextLine();
        // Display the input
        System.out.println("Hello, " + name + "!");
        // Close the Scanner
        scanner.close();
    }
}
