            <h4>Command Line Arguments</h4>
            <p>You can also pass input to a Java program through command-line arguments. Command-line arguments are provided as strings in the main method's parameter</p>
            <ol>
                <li>First, write and compile your Java program. You can use any Java IDE or command-line tools to compile your program into bytecode.</li>
                <li>To pass command-line arguments to your Java program, open a terminal or command prompt and use the Java command followed by the name of your compiled Java class. You can also provide one or more arguments after the class name, separated by spaces.</li>
                <li>Inside your Java program, you can access the command-line arguments by referring to the args parameter in the main method. The args parameter is an array of strings, where each element corresponds to one of the command-line arguments.</li>
                <li>Once you have access to the command-line arguments, you can perform any necessary processing or computations based on the provided arguments.</li>
                <li>Execute your program with the command you used in step 2, providing the desired command-line arguments.</li>
            </ol>
